eople doing front-line work in public sectors such as health, education, social services, and international development, and people management in the private sector.In these fields, organizations have increasingly adopted private-sector management techniques, such as standardized and quantitative measures of performance and an obsession with cost reductions and efficiency. These practices of “new public management” are changing the ways in which front-line workers engage with their clients, students, or patients.Using research drawn from Canada, the United States, Australia, and Denmark, the contributors expose how standardized managerial requirements are created and applied, and how they affect the practicalities of working with people whose lives and experiences are complex and unique.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEthnosociology. 0aHuman servicesxEvaluation. 0aHuman servicesxManagement. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aCampbell, Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorman, Michael K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarville, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDevault, Marjorie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrace, Lauri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Alison I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffith, Alison I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanz, Shauna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCoy, Liza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelon, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v